y:People from Topanga, California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Gray_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Tyler loyal", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Tyler Loyal\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Tyler Holness\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|2000|6|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapper]], [[songwriter]]\n| label            = So Rebel\n| years_active     = 2008\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = Bingz, Phill Mycup, [[A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie]]\n}}\n\n'''Tyler Holness''' (born June 21, 2000), best known by his stage name '''Tyler Loyal''', is an American hip-hop artist and songwriter. He is Boston-born but Brooklyn groomed and holds an air of composure and swagger over anything he touches musically. Originally known for his basketball skills, he is best known for his single, \"The Bottom,\" a remix of \"My Day One,\" by [[A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie]].\n\n== Overview ==\n\nTyler Holness, publicly known as Tyler Loyal, grew up with music running through his veins. His father, Mighty Mystic, was an aspiring reggae artist in Jamaica. What he details as \u201cbeing raised in a studio half my life\u201d, Tyler was at it from a young age. At 8 years old he began making his own beats and writing raps. He would carry this natural talent with him all the way through high school. He attended Malden High School in Massachusetts, and was a stand out player on the basketball team.\n \nWhen Tyler was just 18, he saved enough money to move to Brooklyn, New York. What was originally supposed to be a collegiate basketball career at Saint Joseph College Brooklyn quickly turned into skipping class to go to studio sessions. With no family, friends, or guidance, he found inspiration in the fast paced state. In December 2017, he released \"The Bottom,\" remixing a track from [[A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie]], and found his first nation-wide success. \n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of Music\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:13em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''The Bottom''<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYHgT3GfXJw |title=YouTube |publisher=So Rebel |date= |accessdate=2017-04-28}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: December 28, 2017\n* Label: So Rebel\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Enemy''<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=61n2KfEy300 |title=YouTube |publisher=So Rebel |date= |accessdate=2015-12-23}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: January 24, 2019\n* Label: So Rebel\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Options''<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AR4bVb78Fpo |title=YouTube |publisher= So Rebel |date= |accessdate=2015-03-16}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: December 29, 2019\n* Label: So Rebel\n* Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://tmtv.world/interview/tyler-loyal-talks-new-single-enemy-617-his-father-reggae-artist-mighty-mystic-more/ TMTV Interview]\n* [https://open.spotify.com/artist/7pgbjv3FWqKcMKQckkbd3j Spotify]\n* [https://lyricallemonade.com/p/starlight-tyler-loyal Lyrical Lemonade]\n* [https://www.sjcbears.com/sports/mbkb/2018-19/bios/tyler-holness SJC Bears Sports]\n* [https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/4406709/tyler-holness ESPN]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Tyler Loyal\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Tyler Holness\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|2000|6|21}}\n| birth_place      = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapper]], [[songwriter]]\n| label            = So Rebel\n| years_active     = 2008\u2013present\n| associated_acts  = Bingz, Phill Mycup, [[A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie]]\n}}\n\n'''Tyler Holness''' (born June 21, 2000), best known by his stage name '''Tyler Loyal''', is an American hip-hop artist and songwriter. He is Boston-born but Brooklyn groomed and holds an air of composure and swagger over anything he touches musically. Originally known for his basketball skills, he is best known for his single, \"The Bottom,\" a remix of \"My Day One,\" by [[A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie]].\n\n== Overview ==\n\nTyler Holness, publicly known as Tyler Loyal, grew up with music running through his veins. His father, Mighty Mystic, was an aspiring reggae artist in Jamaica. What he details as \u201cbeing raised in a studio half my life\u201d, Tyler was at it from a young age. At 8 years old he began making his own beats and writing raps. He would carry this natural talent with him all the way through high school. He attended Malden High School in Massachusetts, and was a stand out player on the basketball team.\n \nWhen Tyler was just 18, he saved enough money to move to Brooklyn, New York. What was originally supposed to be a collegiate basketball career at Saint Joseph College Brooklyn quickly turned into skipping class to go to studio sessions. With no family, friends, or guidance, he found inspiration in the fast paced state. In December 2017, he released \"The Bottom,\" remixing a track from [[A Boogie Wit Da Hoodie]], and found his first nation-wide success. \n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of Music\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:13em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17em;\" | Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''The Bottom''<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nYHgT3GfXJw |title=Tyler Loyal Music |publisher=So Rebel |date= |accessdate=2017-04-28}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: December 28, 2017\n* Label: So Rebel\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Enemy''<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=61n2KfEy300 |title=Tyler Loyal Music |publisher=So Rebel |date= |accessdate=2015-12-23}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: January 24, 2019\n* Label: So Rebel\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Options''<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AR4bVb78Fpo |title=Tyler Loyal Music |publisher= So Rebel |date= |accessdate=2015-03-16}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: December 29, 2019\n* Label: So Rebel\n* Format: Digital download\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://tmtv.world/interview/tyler-loyal-talks-new-single-enemy-617-his-father-reggae-artist-mighty-mystic-more/ TMTV Interview]\n* [https://open.spotify.com/artist/7pgbjv3FWqKcMKQckkbd3j Spotify]\n* [https://lyricallemonade.com/p/starlight-tyler-loyal Lyrical Lemonade]\n* [https://www.sjcbears.com/sports/mbkb/2018-19/bios/tyler-holness SJC Bears Sports]\n* [https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/4406709/tyler-holness ESPN]\n", "name_user": "Raoleary", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tyler_loyal"}
{"title_page": "Big Ears", "text_new": "{{about||the Enid Blyton character|Big Ears (character)|the trophy|European Champion Clubs' Cup}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Big Ears\n| image          =Big ears TITLE.JPEG\n| image size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Robert F. McGowan]]\n| producer       = Robert F. McGowan<br>[[Hal Roach]]\n| writer         = [[H. M. Walker]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       =\n| music          = [[Leroy Shield]]<br>[[Marvin Hatley]]\n| cinematography = [[Art Lloyd]]\n| editing        = [[Richard C. Currier]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]]\n| released       = {{start date|1931|8|29}}\n| runtime        = 20' 47\"\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Big Ears''''' is a 1931 ''[[Our Gang]]'' [[short subject|short]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Robert F. McGowan]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite news |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/225657/Big-Ears/overview |work=New York Times| title=Big Ears |accessdate=2008-09-20| first=Ben | last=Ratliff}}</ref> It was the 108th (20th) ''Our Gang'' short that was released.\n\n==Plot==\nWheezer's mother and father continue to fight in an unconvincing and thoroughly hammy fashion over many different silly things, such as the coffee being too cold or the toast being burned. Wheezer overhears his father telling his mother that he is getting her a divorce. Not knowing what a divorce is, Wheezer tells Stymie, Dorothy, and Sherwood. They speculate on what a divorce means, at one point deciding it might be something good. Then Donald tells the gang what a divorce is, and people start sobbing. He even tells Wheezer that he will have no father anymore. His mother might either remarry and give him a stepfather and states that his step father beats him regularly. He also says that maybe his mother will throw him into an orphanage and not want him anymore.\n\nWheezer is frightened so he concocts a plot to make himself abominably sick so that his parents will come together out of concern from him. Wheezer visits a bathroom and his friends pour all the medicine in the medicine cabinet down his throat to make him ill, along with amounts of lard. He indeed gets sick and his plan presumably works. His parents kiss and make up and promise to never fight again and that they love Wheezer very much.\n\n==Notes==\n*''Big Ears'' marked a turnover with [[Allen Hoskins]], [[Mary Ann Jackson]], [[Norman Chaney]], and [[Shirley Jean Rickert]] all leaving the gang. [[Jackie Cooper]] left shortly before the last episode, ''[[Fly My Kite]]''. This left [[Bobby Hutchins]] as the only full-time ''Our Ganger'' left from the silent film era. A few fill-in recurring kids were also left from the silent era and the \"Jackie Cooper era\". Mary Ann's brother Dickie would remain for another two years as a recurring character. It also marked the first episode for [[Sherwood Bailey]], who would have a featured role a few months later in ''[[Dogs is Dogs]]''.\n*''Big Ears'' was removed from the syndicated ''Little Rascals'' television package in 1971 primarily due to its depiction of a dangerous misuse of prescription drugs. Unlike most other episodes, this film was never available on home video until 1995, when it was released on VHS tape.\n\n==Cast==\n===The Gang===\n* [[Bobby Hutchins]] as Wheezer                                   \n* [[Matthew Beard (American actor)|Matthew Beard]] as Stymie     \n* [[Sherwood Bailey]] as Spud                                   \n* [[Dorothy DeBorba]] as Dorothy                                  \n* [[Donald Haines]] as Donald                                     \n* [[Pete the Pup]] as Himself\n\n===Additional cast===\n* Johnnie Mae Beard as Stymie's mother\n* [[Ann Christy]] as Wheezer's mother\n* [[Gordon Douglas (director)|Gordon Douglas]] as Orderly\n* [[Creighton Hale]] as Wheezer's father\n* [[Wilfred Lucas]] as Doctor\n* Dickie Jackson as Kid at hospital (scene deleted)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Our Gang filmography|''Our Gang'' filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0021658}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Ears}}\n[[Category:1931 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert F. McGowan]]\n[[Category:Hal Roach Studios short films]]\n[[Category:1930s comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n[[Category:Our Gang films]]\n", "text_old": "{{for2|the Enid Blyton character|[[Big Ears (character)]]|the trophy|[[European Champion Clubs' Cup]]}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Big Ears\n| image          =Big ears TITLE.JPEG\n| image size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Robert F. McGowan]]\n| producer       = Robert F. McGowan<br>[[Hal Roach]]\n| writer         = [[H. M. Walker]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       =\n| music          = [[Leroy Shield]]<br>[[Marvin Hatley]]\n| cinematography = [[Art Lloyd]]\n| editing        = [[Richard C. Currier]]\n| distributor    = [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]]\n| released       = {{start date|1931|8|29}}\n| runtime        = 20' 47\"\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Big Ears''''' is a 1931 ''[[Our Gang]]'' [[short subject|short]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Robert F. McGowan]].<ref name=\"NY Times\">{{cite news |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/225657/Big-Ears/overview |work=New York Times| title=Big Ears |accessdate=2008-09-20| first=Ben | last=Ratliff}}</ref> It was the 108th (20th) ''Our Gang'' short that was released.\n\n==Plot==\nWheezer's mother and father continue to fight in an unconvincing and thoroughly hammy fashion over many different silly things, such as the coffee being too cold or the toast being burned. Wheezer overhears his father telling his mother that he is getting her a divorce. Not knowing what a divorce is, Wheezer tells Stymie, Dorothy, and Sherwood. They speculate on what a divorce means, at one point deciding it might be something good. Then Donald tells the gang what a divorce is, and people start sobbing. He even tells Wheezer that he will have no father anymore. His mother might either remarry and give him a stepfather and states that his step father beats him regularly. He also says that maybe his mother will throw him into an orphanage and not want him anymore.\n\nWheezer is frightened so he concocts a plot to make himself abominably sick so that his parents will come together out of concern from him. Wheezer visits a bathroom and his friends pour all the medicine in the medicine cabinet down his throat to make him ill, along with amounts of lard. He indeed gets sick and his plan presumably works. His parents kiss and make up and promise to never fight again and that they love Wheezer very much.\n\n==Notes==\n*''Big Ears'' marked a turnover with [[Allen Hoskins]], [[Mary Ann Jackson]], [[Norman Chaney]], and [[Shirley Jean Rickert]] all leaving the gang. [[Jackie Cooper]] left shortly before the last episode, ''[[Fly My Kite]]''. This left [[Bobby Hutchins]] as the only full-time ''Our Ganger'' left from the silent film era. A few fill-in recurring kids were also left from the silent era and the \"Jackie Cooper era\". Mary Ann's brother Dickie would remain for another two years as a recurring character. It also marked the first episode for [[Sherwood Bailey]], who would have a featured role a few months later in ''[[Dogs is Dogs]]''.\n*''Big Ears'' was removed from the syndicated ''Little Rascals'' television package in 1971 primarily due to its depiction of a dangerous misuse of prescription drugs. Unlike most other episodes, this film was never available on home video until 1995, when it was released on VHS tape.\n\n==Cast==\n===The Gang===\n* [[Bobby Hutchins]] as Wheezer                                   \n* [[Matthew Beard (American actor)|Matthew Beard]] as Stymie     \n* [[Sherwood Bailey]] as Spud                                   \n* [[Dorothy DeBorba]] as Dorothy                                  \n* [[Donald Haines]] as Donald                                     \n* [[Pete the Pup]] as Himself\n\n===Additional cast===\n* Johnnie Mae Beard as Stymie's mother\n* [[Ann Christy]] as Wheezer's mother\n* [[Gordon Douglas (director)|Gordon Douglas]] as Orderly\n* [[Creighton Hale]] as Wheezer's father\n* [[Wilfred Lucas]] as Doctor\n* Dickie Jackson as Kid at hospital (scene deleted)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Our Gang filmography|''Our Gang'' filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0021658}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Big Ears}}\n[[Category:1931 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert F. McGowan]]\n[[Category:Hal Roach Studios short films]]\n[[Category:1930s comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films made before the MPAA Production Code]]\n[[Category:Our Gang films]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Ears"}
{"title_page": "Quadrant Park", "text_new": "{{coord|53.436|-2.993|display=title}} \n{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = Quadrant Park\n| nickname               = Quaddie<ref name=\"intotheworld\"/>  \n| logo_image             = \n| logo_caption           = \n| image                  = \n| image_size             = \n| image_alt              = \n| caption                = \n| pushpin_map            = \n| pushpin_mapsize        = \n| pushpin_map_caption    = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| address                = Derby Road in [[Bootle]], north of the city of Liverpool, in a converted warehouse\n| location               = [[Bootle]], [[England]]\n| coordinates            = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| type                   = [[Club music|Club]]\n| genre                  = [[acid house]], [[Italo house]], [[Techno]], [[electronic dance music]]\n| broke_ground           = \n| built                  = \n| opened                 = 1988<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| renovated              = \n| expanded               = \n| closed                 = December 31, 1991\n| demolished             = \n| owner                  = \n| operator               = \n| surface                = \n| scoreboard             = \n| production             = \n| cost                   = \n| architect              = \n| project_manager        = \n| structural engineer    = \n| services engineer      = \n| general_contractor     = \n| main_contractors       = \n| seating_type           = \n| capacity               = 2,400<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reynolds|first1=Simon|title=Energy Flash: A Journey Through Rave Music and Dance Culture|url=https://books.google.ae/books?id=CXPZyYHLd-kC&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=quadrant+park+liverpool+1988&source=bl&ots=KbaAodXtzL&sig=JdSBq9ok6dfptyvoZ9_IHujCzXs&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20liverpool%201988&f=false|website=books.google.ae|publisher=Faber & Faber, 2013|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n| suites                 = \n| record_attendance      = \n| dimensions             = \n| field_shape            = \n| acreage                = \n| volume                 = \n| tenants                = \n| embedded               = \n| website                = [http://www.quadrantparkreunions.com QuadrantParkReunions.com]\n| publictransit          = \n}}\n'''Quadrant Park'''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Beat Goes On exhibition|url=http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/wml/exhibitions/thebeatgoeson/sites_scenes.aspx|website=liverpoolmuseums.org.uk|publisher=Liverpool Museums|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> also known as the '''Quad''' or '''Quaddie''' <ref>{{cite news|last1=Weston|first1=Alan|title=Trip down memory lane as we revisit some of Merseyside's iconic nightclubs|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/nostalgia/take-trip-down-memory-lane-10645166|accessdate=26 October 2017|work=liverpoolecho|date=25 December 2015}}</ref> was a [[nightclub]] in [[Bootle]], [[United Kingdom|UK]] opened during the late 1980s to the early 1990s.<ref name=\"intotheworld\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=BWf4J6yn9zAC&pg=PA450&lpg=PA450&dq=%22quadrant+park%22+club&source=bl&ots=6Z1OhoXK7K&sig=l0rYBDbfQkAca5DVuK13gLi6yu4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAzgoahUKEwjP5bmHkP7HAhVTFZIKHYihA8k#v=onepage&q=%22quadrant%20park%22%20club&f=false ''Generation Ecstasy: Into the World of Techno and Rave Culture'' by Simon Reynolds]</ref> and one of the most important in the UK at the time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Childs|first1=Peter|last2=Storry|first2=Michael|title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary British Culture|date=May 13, 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1134755554|page=113|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tlsKXeRt0wgC&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&dq=Quadrant+Park+nightclub++Liverpool,&source=bl&ots=sLc3GB3uGY&sig=4YqffFWyn4Cbl8T6zwGflOWC3zg&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Quadrant%20Park%20nightclub%20%20Liverpool%2C&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and was known to attract a number of international guest [[Disc jockey|DJs]]. The main styles of music played were [[Italo house]] and [[acid house]], retrospectively it could also be defined an early [[Superclub]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duffy|first1=Tom|title=Catching up with those superstar DJs from Quadrant Park|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/catching-up-those-superstar-djs-12796778|accessdate=25 September 2017|work=liverpoolecho|date=25 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe nightclub was located on Derby Road in [[Bootle]], north of the city of Liverpool, in a converted warehouse.  The building was originally an [[Owen Owen]] warehouse,<ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\">{{cite book|last1=Webley|first1=Elvis|title=Hooligans, Doormen, and the Ten-Metre Walk: Ten-Metre Walk|date=2013|publisher=Balboa Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=9781452576626|pages=84\u201385|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h6b6G00rrKkC&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=famous+liverpool+nightclub+the+quadrant+park&source=bl&ots=BpOUuL-gnj&sig=dZiE49SDhasUl8FCpLdO7XQ8Npw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbpcG4p43XAhWMuo8KHfrQBeMQ6AEIZjAN#v=onepage&q=famous%20liverpool%20nightclub%20the%20quadrant%20park&f=false|language=en}}</ref> which was purchased by steel magnate James Spencer in the late 1980s to convert into a nightclub and snooker hall. A \"Heritage Market\" was opened shortly after to make use of the large unused lower floor space at the rear. Originally opened in the late 1980s as a [[Billiard hall|snooker hall]] <ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\"/> and mainstream nightclub, there was also a market in the downstairs warehouse area, and the upstairs contained a small [[social club]] (the ''Harlequin Suite'') <ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\"/> which could be hired out for social occasions. After the Sunday market trade had moved to a nearby dock warehouse (Stanley Market), Quadrant Park started holding all night [[rave]]s in the then-vacant space.<ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\"/> A loop-hole in a Sefton council licensing law enabled Quadrant Park to be the only legal all-night rave in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reynolds|first1=Simon|title=Energy Flash: A Journey Through Rave Music and Dance Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CXPZyYHLd-kC&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=quadrant+park+was+legal+all+nighter&source=bl&ots=KbaAlcWwwP&sig=ZrBkoiOnzNefUJ5Nxv98N9nFOjg&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20was%20legal%20all%20nighter&f=false|website=books.google.lk|publisher=Faber & Faber, Jul 4, 2013|accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Strachan Rob|first1=Marion Leonard|title=The Beat Goes on: Liverpool, Popular Music and the Changing City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zx_OpMptTFQC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=quadrant+park+was+legal+all+nighter&source=bl&ots=-6XFqAGw4G&sig=d5kB4YXlKs2MQchKDbHCoyI63PQ&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20was%20legal%20all%20nighter&f=false|website=books.google.lk|publisher=Liverpool University Press, 2010|accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref> as the venue did not sell alcohol.<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\">\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=WCylBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT245&lpg=PT245&dq=%22quadrant+park%22+club&source=bl&ots=xb6WymOj1p&sig=Q6K7pYaSFEPQ3emcCwal7xoPiSs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAjgoahUKEwjP5bmHkP7HAhVTFZIKHYihA8k#v=onepage&q=%22quadrant%20park%22%20club&f=false ''Life After Dark: A History of British Nightclubs & Music Venues'' by Dave Haslam]</ref> Quadrant Park's main period of activity began in early January 1990 with a capacity of 2,400, Quadrant Park began focusing on house music in early 1990. The club was dubbed \"The Quad\" and in October 1990 it opened the Pavilion, the first weekly legal all-nighter in Britain. Pavilion was put on in the basement below the main club.<ref name=\"intotheworld\"/> Some party goers would travel long distances to get to the venue; from London, Glasgow, Birmingham and even as far away as Aberdeen.<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\"/> Near the end of 1990, the club obtained a licence to stay open to six o'clock.<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\"/>\n\n==DJs==\n\n[[Mike Knowler (DJ)|Mike Knowler]] was the initial resident DJ,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Haslam|first1=Dave|title=Life After Dark: A History of British Nightclubs & Music Venues|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WCylBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT245&lpg=PT245&dq=quadrant+park+liverpool&source=bl&ots=xb6XBjKi6n&sig=T4_KxmrjwkmePhGNclFDoyxdEeA&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20liverpool&f=false|website=books.google.com|publisher=Simon and Schuster, Aug 13, 2015|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> and soon invited DJ partner [[Andy Carroll (DJ)|Andy Carroll]] to join him.<ref name=\"_lquardmike\">\n{{cite news\n| title       =Quadrant Park History\n| first       =Mike\n| last        =Knowler\n| url         =http://www.mikeknowler.com/quad.info.html\n| newspaper   =\n| publisher   =mikeknowler.com\n| date        =\n| accessdate  = 2015-09-03\n}}</ref> Carroll and Knowler had previously helped bring [[acid house music]] to the city of Liverpool, DJing at ''The State''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Jade|title=Worth getting in a State about - one of Liverpool's premier dance venues revisited|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/worth-getting-state---one-3435117|website=liverpoolecho.co.uk|publisher=Liverpool Echo Newspaper, 30 Jan 2010|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> nightclub in Dale Street.<ref name=\"_lquardmike\"/> When the all-nighter opened in November 1990, John Kelly,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Crispy|first1=Don|title=Halloween hi-jinks|url=http://archive.metropolis.co.jp/tokyo/500/clubs.asp|website=archive.metropolis.co.jp|publisher=Mtetropolis Magazine Japan|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> [[Cream (nightclub)|James Barton]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Cream: The club that changed the world.|url=http://tonightinliverpool.com/news/stuff/cream-the-club-that-changed-the-world|website=tonightinliverpool.com|publisher=Tonight in Liverpool Webzine UK|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> and Gary J joined the resident DJ crew.<ref name=\"_lquardmike\"/>  Guest DJs at Quadrant Park included [[Laurent Garnier]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview Laurent Garnier|url=http://www.music-news.com/showreview.asp?H=Laurent-Garnier&nReviewID=4864|website=music-news.com|publisher=Music News|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> [[Derrick May (musician)|Derrick May]], [[Frankie Bones]],<ref name=\"_lquardmike\"/> [[Fabio]], [[Grooverider]], [[Rob Tissera (DJ)|Rob Tissera]], [[Trevor Fung (DJ)|Trevor Fung]], [[Joey Beltram]] and [[Sasha (DJ)|Sasha]].<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\"/> Knowler was given the Thursday night gig in January 1990, and was later also given the residency of the club's Friday and Saturday nights.<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\"/>\n\n==Live PAs==\nA number of live performances at Quadrant Park included: [[Anticappella]], [[Baby D (dance group)|Baby D]], [[Baby Ford]], [[Bassomatic]], [[Bizarre Inc]], [[Dream Frequency]], [[Jam MCs]], [[K-Klass]], [[Katherine E]], [[LFO (British band)|LFO]], [[N-Joi]], Mr Monday, [[Nightmares on Wax]],  and [[Shades of Rhythm]].\n\n==Closure==\nThe club survived until 31 December 1991, despite considerable and persistent licensing issues and unfavourable media attention in newspapers.<ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\"/> Quadrant Park closed voluntarily that night, following an incident of robbery and a stabbing.<ref name=\"intotheworld\"/> The building has since been demolished and has been replaced with a waste recycling centre.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitehurst|first1=Andrew|title=BIZARRE INC 'PLAYING WITH KNIVES' The seminal tracks that changed dance music forever|url=http://djmag.com/content/bizarre-inc-playing-knives|website=djmag.com|publisher=DJ Magazine UK|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural impact and legacy==\nThe club was featured in an exhibition hosted at the [[World Museum]] as part of the [[European Capital of Culture]] in July 2008 of which Liverpool was the host city.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Beat Goes On Sixty years of Liverpool music is celebrated in a new exhibition at World Museum Liverpool.|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/content/articles/2008/07/09/cap_culture_beat_goes_on_feature.shtml|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of electronic dance music venues]]\n*[[Superclub]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last1=Haslam|first1=Dave|title=Life After Dark: A History of British Nightclubs & Music Venues|date=2015|publisher=Simon & Schuster UK|isbn=9780857206985|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Life-After-Dark-History-Nightclubs/dp/0857206982|language=English}} \n*{{cite book|last1=Reynolds|first1=Simon|title=Generation Ecstasy: Into the World of Techno and Rave Culture|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136783166|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BWf4J6yn9zAC&dq=%22quadrant+park%22+club&source=gbs_navlinks_s|language=en}} \n* {{cite book|last1=Reynolds|first1=Simon|title=Energy Flash: A Journey Through Rave Music and Dance Culture|date=2013|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=9780571289141|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CXPZyYHLd-kC&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=quadrant+park+was+legal+all+nighter&source=bl&ots=KbaAlcWwwP&sig=ZrBkoiOnzNefUJ5Nxv98N9nFOjg&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20was%20legal%20all%20nighter&f=false|language=en}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Webley|first1=Elvis|title=Hooligans, Doormen, and the Ten-Metre Walk: Ten-Metre Walk|date=2013|publisher=Balboa Press|isbn=9781452576626|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h6b6G00rrKkC&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=famous+liverpool+nightclub+the+quadrant+park&source=bl&ots=BpOUuL-gnj&sig=dZiE49SDhasUl8FCpLdO7XQ8Npw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbpcG4p43XAhWMuo8KHfrQBeMQ6AEIZjAN#v=onepage&q=famous%20liverpool%20nightclub%20the%20quadrant%20park&f=false|language=en}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.quadrantparkreunions.com QuadrantParkReunions.com - the official home of the original Quadrant Park DJs and LIVE events for 2011]\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20151003122010/http://www.quadrantpark.com/index.php - official website since 2002.   \n*http://www.mikeknowler.com\n\n[[Category:Nightclubs in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Culture in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music venues]]\n", "text_old": "{{coord|53.436|-2.993|display=title}} \n{{Infobox venue\n| name                   = Quadrant Park\n| nickname               = Quaddie<ref name=\"intotheworld\"/>  \n| logo_image             = \n| logo_caption           = \n| image                  = \n| image_size             = \n| image_alt              = \n| caption                = \n| pushpin_map            = \n| pushpin_mapsize        = \n| pushpin_map_caption    = \n| pushpin_label_position = \n| address                = Derby Road in [[Bootle]], north of the city of Liverpool, in a converted warehouse\n| location               = [[Bootle]], [[England]]\n| coordinates            = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| type                   = [[Club music|Club]]\n| genre                  = [[acid house]], [[Italo house]], [[Techno]], [[electronic dance music]]\n| broke_ground           = \n| built                  = \n| opened                 = 1988<!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| renovated              = \n| expanded               = \n| closed                 = December 31, 1991\n| demolished             = \n| owner                  = \n| operator               = \n| surface                = \n| scoreboard             = \n| production             = \n| cost                   = \n| architect              = \n| project_manager        = \n| structural engineer    = \n| services engineer      = \n| general_contractor     = \n| main_contractors       = \n| seating_type           = \n| capacity               = 2,400<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reynolds|first1=Simon|title=Energy Flash: A Journey Through Rave Music and Dance Culture|url=https://books.google.ae/books?id=CXPZyYHLd-kC&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=quadrant+park+liverpool+1988&source=bl&ots=KbaAodXtzL&sig=JdSBq9ok6dfptyvoZ9_IHujCzXs&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20liverpool%201988&f=false|website=books.google.ae|publisher=Faber & Faber, 2013|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref>\n| suites                 = \n| record_attendance      = \n| dimensions             = \n| field_shape            = \n| acreage                = \n| volume                 = \n| tenants                = \n| embedded               = \n| website                = [http://www.quadrantparkreunions.com QuadrantParkReunions.com]\n| publictransit          = \n}}\n'''Quadrant Park'''<ref>{{cite web|title=The Beat Goes On exhibition|url=http://www.liverpoolmuseums.org.uk/wml/exhibitions/thebeatgoeson/sites_scenes.aspx|website=liverpoolmuseums.org.uk|publisher=Liverpool Museums|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> also known as the '''Quad''' or '''Quaddie''' <ref>{{cite news|last1=Weston|first1=Alan|title=Trip down memory lane as we revisit some of Merseyside's iconic nightclubs|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/nostalgia/take-trip-down-memory-lane-10645166|accessdate=26 October 2017|work=liverpoolecho|date=25 December 2015}}</ref> was a [[nightclub]] in [[Bootle]], [[United Kingdom|UK]] opened during the late 1980s to the early 1990s.<ref name=\"intotheworld\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=BWf4J6yn9zAC&pg=PA450&lpg=PA450&dq=%22quadrant+park%22+club&source=bl&ots=6Z1OhoXK7K&sig=l0rYBDbfQkAca5DVuK13gLi6yu4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCoQ6AEwAzgoahUKEwjP5bmHkP7HAhVTFZIKHYihA8k#v=onepage&q=%22quadrant%20park%22%20club&f=false ''Generation Ecstasy: Into the World of Techno and Rave Culture'' by Simon Reynolds]</ref> and one of the most important in the UK at the time.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Childs|first1=Peter|last2=Storry|first2=Michael|title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary British Culture|date=May 13, 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1134755554|page=113|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tlsKXeRt0wgC&pg=PA113&lpg=PA113&dq=Quadrant+Park+nightclub++Liverpool,&source=bl&ots=sLc3GB3uGY&sig=4YqffFWyn4Cbl8T6zwGflOWC3zg&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Quadrant%20Park%20nightclub%20%20Liverpool%2C&f=false|language=en}}</ref> and was known to attract a number of international guest [[Disc jockey|DJs]]. The main styles of music played were [[Italo house]] and [[acid house]], retrospectively it could also be defined an early [[Superclub]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duffy|first1=Tom|title=Catching up with those superstar DJs from Quadrant Park|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/catching-up-those-superstar-djs-12796778|accessdate=25 September 2017|work=liverpoolecho|date=25 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nThe nightclub was located on Derby Road in [[Bootle]], north of the city of Liverpool, in a converted warehouse.  The building was originally an [[Owen Owen]] warehouse,<ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\">{{cite book|last1=Webley|first1=Elvis|title=Hooligans, Doormen, and the Ten-Metre Walk: Ten-Metre Walk|date=2013|publisher=Balboa Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=9781452576626|pages=84\u201385|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h6b6G00rrKkC&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=famous+liverpool+nightclub+the+quadrant+park&source=bl&ots=BpOUuL-gnj&sig=dZiE49SDhasUl8FCpLdO7XQ8Npw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbpcG4p43XAhWMuo8KHfrQBeMQ6AEIZjAN#v=onepage&q=famous%20liverpool%20nightclub%20the%20quadrant%20park&f=false|language=en}}</ref> which was purchased by steel magnate James Spencer in the late 1980s to convert into a nightclub and snooker hall. A \"Heritage Market\" was opened shortly after to make use of the large unused lower floor space at the rear. Originally opened in the late 1980s as a [[Billiard hall|snooker hall]] <ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\"/> and mainstream nightclub, there was also a market in the downstairs warehouse area, and the upstairs contained a small [[social club]] (the ''Harlequin Suite'') <ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\"/> which could be hired out for social occasions. After the Sunday market trade had moved to a nearby dock warehouse (Stanley Market), Quadrant Park started holding all night [[rave]]s in the then-vacant space.<ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\"/> A loop-hole in a Sefton council licensing law enabled Quadrant Park to be the only legal all-night rave in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reynolds|first1=Simon|title=Energy Flash: A Journey Through Rave Music and Dance Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CXPZyYHLd-kC&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=quadrant+park+was+legal+all+nighter&source=bl&ots=KbaAlcWwwP&sig=ZrBkoiOnzNefUJ5Nxv98N9nFOjg&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20was%20legal%20all%20nighter&f=false|website=books.google.lk|publisher=Faber & Faber, Jul 4, 2013|accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Strachan Rob|first1=Marion Leonard|title=The Beat Goes on: Liverpool, Popular Music and the Changing City|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zx_OpMptTFQC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=quadrant+park+was+legal+all+nighter&source=bl&ots=-6XFqAGw4G&sig=d5kB4YXlKs2MQchKDbHCoyI63PQ&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20was%20legal%20all%20nighter&f=false|website=books.google.lk|publisher=Liverpool University Press, 2010|accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref> as the venue did not sell alcohol.<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\">\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=WCylBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT245&lpg=PT245&dq=%22quadrant+park%22+club&source=bl&ots=xb6WymOj1p&sig=Q6K7pYaSFEPQ3emcCwal7xoPiSs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAjgoahUKEwjP5bmHkP7HAhVTFZIKHYihA8k#v=onepage&q=%22quadrant%20park%22%20club&f=false ''Life After Dark: A History of British Nightclubs & Music Venues'' by Dave Haslam]</ref> Quadrant Park's main period of activity began in early January 1990 with a capacity of 2,400, Quadrant Park began focusing on house music in early 1990. The club was dubbed \"The Quad\" and in October 1990 it opened the Pavilion, the first weekly legal all-nighter in Britain. Pavilion was put on in the basement below the main club.<ref name=\"intotheworld\"/> Some party goers would travel long distances to get to the venue; from London, Glasgow, Birmingham and even as far away as Aberdeen.<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\"/> Near the end of 1990, the club obtained a licence to stay open to six o'clock.<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\"/>\n\n==DJ's==\n\n[[Mike Knowler (DJ)|Mike Knowler]] was the initial resident DJ,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Haslam|first1=Dave|title=Life After Dark: A History of British Nightclubs & Music Venues|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WCylBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT245&lpg=PT245&dq=quadrant+park+liverpool&source=bl&ots=xb6XBjKi6n&sig=T4_KxmrjwkmePhGNclFDoyxdEeA&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20liverpool&f=false|website=books.google.com|publisher=Simon and Schuster, Aug 13, 2015|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref> and soon invited DJ partner [[Andy Carroll (DJ)|Andy Carroll]] to join him.<ref name=\"_lquardmike\">\n{{cite news\n| title       =Quadrant Park History\n| first       =Mike\n| last        =Knowler\n| url         =http://www.mikeknowler.com/quad.info.html\n| newspaper   =\n| publisher   =mikeknowler.com\n| date        =\n| accessdate  = 2015-09-03\n}}</ref> Carroll and Knowler had previously helped bring [[acid house music]] to the city of Liverpool, DJing at ''The State''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Jade|title=Worth getting in a State about - one of Liverpool's premier dance venues revisited|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/worth-getting-state---one-3435117|website=liverpoolecho.co.uk|publisher=Liverpool Echo Newspaper, 30 Jan 2010|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> nightclub in Dale Street.<ref name=\"_lquardmike\"/> When the all-nighter opened in November 1990, John Kelly,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Crispy|first1=Don|title=Halloween hi-jinks|url=http://archive.metropolis.co.jp/tokyo/500/clubs.asp|website=archive.metropolis.co.jp|publisher=Mtetropolis Magazine Japan|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> [[Cream (nightclub)|James Barton]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Cream: The club that changed the world.|url=http://tonightinliverpool.com/news/stuff/cream-the-club-that-changed-the-world|website=tonightinliverpool.com|publisher=Tonight in Liverpool Webzine UK|accessdate=4 October 2015}}</ref> and Gary J joined the resident DJ crew.<ref name=\"_lquardmike\"/>  Guest DJs at Quadrant Park included [[Laurent Garnier]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview Laurent Garnier|url=http://www.music-news.com/showreview.asp?H=Laurent-Garnier&nReviewID=4864|website=music-news.com|publisher=Music News|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref> [[Derrick May (musician)|Derrick May]], [[Frankie Bones]],<ref name=\"_lquardmike\"/> [[Fabio]], [[Grooverider]], [[Rob Tissera (DJ)|Rob Tissera]], [[Trevor Fung (DJ)|Trevor Fung]], [[Joey Beltram]] and [[Sasha (DJ)|Sasha]].<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\"/> Knowler was given the Thursday night gig in January 1990, and was later also given the residency of the club's Friday and Saturday nights.<ref name=\"_mhaslamfd\"/>\n\n==Live PA's==\nA number of live performances at Quadrant Park included: [[Anticappella]], [[Baby D (dance group)|Baby D]], [[Baby Ford]], [[Bassomatic]], [[Bizarre Inc]], [[Dream Frequency]], [[Jam MC's]], [[K-Klass]], [[Katherine E]], [[LFO (British band)|LFO]], [[N-Joi]], Mr Monday, [[Nightmares on Wax]],  and [[Shades of Rhythm]].\n\n==Closure==\nThe club survived until 31 December 1991, despite considerable and persistent licensing issues and unfavourable media attention in newspapers.<ref name=\"Webley-pp.84-85\"/> Quadrant Park closed voluntarily that night, following an incident of robbery and a stabbing.<ref name=\"intotheworld\"/> The building has since been demolished and has been replaced with a waste recycling centre.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Whitehurst|first1=Andrew|title=BIZARRE INC 'PLAYING WITH KNIVES' The seminal tracks that changed dance music forever|url=http://djmag.com/content/bizarre-inc-playing-knives|website=djmag.com|publisher=DJ Magazine UK|accessdate=2 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural impact and legacy==\nThe club was featured in an exhibition hosted at the [[World Museum]] as part of the [[European Capital of Culture]] in July 2008 of which Liverpool was the host city.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Beat Goes On Sixty years of Liverpool music is celebrated in a new exhibition at World Museum Liverpool.|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/liverpool/content/articles/2008/07/09/cap_culture_beat_goes_on_feature.shtml|website=bbc.co.uk|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=3 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of electronic dance music venues]]\n*[[Superclub]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book|last1=Haslam|first1=Dave|title=Life After Dark: A History of British Nightclubs & Music Venues|date=2015|publisher=Simon & Schuster UK|isbn=9780857206985|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Life-After-Dark-History-Nightclubs/dp/0857206982|language=English}} \n*{{cite book|last1=Reynolds|first1=Simon|title=Generation Ecstasy: Into the World of Techno and Rave Culture|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136783166|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BWf4J6yn9zAC&dq=%22quadrant+park%22+club&source=gbs_navlinks_s|language=en}} \n* {{cite book|last1=Reynolds|first1=Simon|title=Energy Flash: A Journey Through Rave Music and Dance Culture|date=2013|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=9780571289141|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CXPZyYHLd-kC&pg=PT99&lpg=PT99&dq=quadrant+park+was+legal+all+nighter&source=bl&ots=KbaAlcWwwP&sig=ZrBkoiOnzNefUJ5Nxv98N9nFOjg&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=quadrant%20park%20was%20legal%20all%20nighter&f=false|language=en}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Webley|first1=Elvis|title=Hooligans, Doormen, and the Ten-Metre Walk: Ten-Metre Walk|date=2013|publisher=Balboa Press|isbn=9781452576626|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h6b6G00rrKkC&pg=PA84&lpg=PA84&dq=famous+liverpool+nightclub+the+quadrant+park&source=bl&ots=BpOUuL-gnj&sig=dZiE49SDhasUl8FCpLdO7XQ8Npw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjbpcG4p43XAhWMuo8KHfrQBeMQ6AEIZjAN#v=onepage&q=famous%20liverpool%20nightclub%20the%20quadrant%20park&f=false|language=en}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.quadrantparkreunions.com QuadrantParkReunions.com - the official home of the original Quadrant Park DJs and LIVE events for 2011]\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20151003122010/http://www.quadrantpark.com/index.php - official website since 2002.   \n*http://www.mikeknowler.com\n\n[[Category:Nightclubs in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Culture in Liverpool]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music venues]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadrant_Park"}
